\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 The League follows a few simple rules: 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
1: You enter the Omni-League by setting aside a single On the Edge Starter Deck. Designate a starter as your Omni-League deck before you open it, instead of opening multiple starters and choosing the best. This guarantee of fairness depends upon the honor
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
of the players.You may choose from the Limited, Unlimited, or Standard Version printings, but you should understand that the improved card distribution in the Standard Version tends to provide more balanced decks. If Standard is unavailable in your area, 
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 U\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 nlimited is a better choice than Limited for the same reason. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 Once you've chosen your Starter Deck, open it to check out your initial League set. Your set is defined as all the cards you have available for Omni-League play. Your League deck, on the other\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
 hand, is the forty or more cards you chose to play with at the start of any game. Cards left out of your deck form your reserves. You can swap cards from your deck to your reserves and back as often as you wish (except while a game is in progress, of cou
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 se). 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
2: Omni-League games are played using the Standard Version Rules of Play, found in Standard Version Starter Decks. All errata are in effect. You can read the current errata and rulings by picking up a copy of Surviving On the Edge, the player's guid
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 e to On the Edge (AG2600, ISBN 1-887801-22-7). Up-to-date errata and rulings can also be found on Atlas Games world wide web site (www.atlas-games.com). 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 3: Omni-League games may be played anywhere, at any time, with any number of League members. You may \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 even play with teams, as long as the teammates agree on how to divide the stakes. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 4: Omni-League games are played for stakes -- one card which each player offers as ante for the match. Stakes are the only way that you may alter the composition of your Om\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
ni-League set. In games with more than two players, all players must agree beforehand how the stakes will be divided up. Each player has the power to decide which cards to risk and which to keep hold of as useful parts of their deck. The best strategy is 
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
o offer cards out of your reserves, since they are not worth as much to you as they may be to your opponent. The best stakes are those that benefit all players. This avoids tedious exchanges of marginal cards and instead improves the winner's deck in the 
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 ajority of games. As a result of the system of stakes, the number of cards in a set offers a rough estimate of the deck's strength. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 5: Each League member puts a distinctive mark on every card in his set, whether they were part of the original set or were\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
 won later as stakes. You can be as creative as you want in marking your cards, but be sure to mark the card face, not its back. Omni-League marks identify the previous owner(s) of the cards in the League, making cards with many marks valuable trophies. T
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 ese marks also serve to keep your Omni-League set separate from your regular On the Edge collections. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 6: Trading cards (except in stakes), bringing cards in from other decks or boosters, playing for stakes against non-League decks, and so on are not allo\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 
wed. The only way to change your League set is by playing for stakes against other League players. Intentionally throwing games in order to facilitate the exchange of cards is effectively trading and is not allowed. Players are bound by their honor to cha
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 ge their sets only though fair wins in legal games. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 7: When your League set drops below fifty cards, you may choose to retire the set and begin again with another Starter Deck. If you drop below forty cards, you must retire your set because it can no lon
\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 ger field a legal deck. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 8: To repeat the obvious, the Omni-League is an honor-based system. Play for fun and be honorable. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 9: Players may play without stakes, use house rules, or utilize other variations of standarad On the Edge, as long as all partici\hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 pants agree on them beforehand. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af4\loch\f0 10: The Omni-League is composed entirely of players. It has no rules other than those found here, and has no central administration. 
